Date:  0/0/1851
Source:  Southern Districts of NZ
Author:  SHORTLAND
Vol / Page:  154
Edition:
Quote:  The name Tovy Poenammoo, or, as it would [155] now be written, Te Wai-pounamu, meaning the Pounamu-water, by many still imagined to be that of the Middle Island, is, as Captain Cook suspected, `only the name of a particular place, where the natives got the green talc, or stone, of which they made their ornaments and tools, and not a general name of the whole southern district.'
